# Agent Token Strategy

Complements `rtk-token-optimization.mdc` (CLI output compression) with higher-level cost controls.

## Model Routing

| Tier | When | Cost |
|------|------|------|
| `fast` / Haiku | Subagent exploration, file reading, simple lookups, grep tasks | ~1x |
| Default / Sonnet | Day-to-day coding, reviews, test writing, implementation | ~4x |
| Opus | Complex architecture, multi-step reasoning, debugging subtle issues | ~19x |

- Default to the cheapest tier that meets the task's needs
- Use `fast` model for Task tool subagents when doing exploration, file reading, or test running
- Only escalate to Opus for multi-step reasoning or architectural decisions

## Context Window Hygiene

- Prefer subagents (Task tool) for exploration — they read many files but return only a summary, keeping main context clean
- At logical task boundaries (after research, after debugging, before new phase), consider context as potentially stale
- Avoid reading large files (>1K lines) in main context — use SemanticSearch or Grep scoped to that file instead
- When generating plans or reports, write to files rather than outputting long text inline

## Subagent Cost Control

- For exploration tasks that only need file reading and searching: use `model: "fast"`
- For implementation tasks requiring code generation: use default model
- One focused task per subagent — avoid multi-purpose subagent prompts
- Include explicit return instructions ("return only: X, Y, Z") to prevent verbose subagent responses

## MCP Server Budget

- Keep under 10 MCP servers enabled per project — each adds tool definitions to context
- Prefer CLI tools when they exist (`gh` over GitHub MCP for simple operations)
- Disable unused MCP servers in project config

## Prompt Cache Preservation

Prompt caching works by prefix matching — the API caches from the start of the
request up to each cache_control breakpoint. Any change anywhere in the prefix
invalidates everything after it. Design the entire system around this constraint.

### Content Ordering (cache-friendly)

1. Static system prompt & Tools (globally cached)
2. CLAUDE.md / AGENTS.md / Rules (cached per project)
3. Session context — env, MCP, output style (cached per session)
4. Conversation messages (per-turn)

### Rules

- NEVER add or remove tools mid-session — use defer_loading stubs + ToolSearch
- NEVER switch models mid-session — use subagents for different model tiers
  (switching from Opus to Haiku mid-conversation rebuilds the cache from scratch,
  making it more expensive than keeping Opus)
- Use messages (next-turn user message or tool result) to convey updates
  (time changes, file changes) instead of modifying the system prompt
- EnterPlanMode / ExitPlanMode are tools, not tool-set swaps — tool definitions
  stay constant; mode transitions happen via tool calls and system messages
- Avoid non-deterministic tool definition ordering across requests
- Avoid timestamps or volatile data in the system prompt
- Monitor cache hit rate as a key operational metric — treat cache breaks as incidents

### Cache-Safe Forking

When running compaction or subagent work, use the same system prompt, user
context, and tool definitions as the parent conversation. Append the new
instruction as a user message at the end to maximize prefix cache reuse.
This applies to:
- Compaction (summarizing conversation history)
- Subagent spawning (explore, review, fix subagents)
- Skill execution in forked contexts

### Frozen Snapshot Pattern

Core context files (`MEMORY.md`, `AGENTS.md`, always-applied rules) are loaded
once at session start and treated as **immutable for the session lifetime**.

- Mid-session writes to `MEMORY.md` persist to disk but do NOT update the
  in-context copy — the system prompt prefix stays identical across turns
- This guarantees prompt cache hits on the static prefix (Layers 1-2 in the
  Content Ordering above) for the entire session
- Corollary: do not read `MEMORY.md` again mid-session expecting fresh content;
  if you need the updated version, spawn a subagent (which starts a new context)

**Files covered by the frozen-snapshot discipline:**

| File | Loaded at | Mutability |
|------|-----------|------------|
| `AGENTS.md` | Session start | Frozen — edits take effect next session |
| `MEMORY.md` | Session start | Frozen — writes persist to disk only |
| Always-applied `.mdc` rules | Session start | Frozen |
| MCP tool definitions | Session start | Frozen — never add/remove mid-session |

**Why this matters:** A single character change in any frozen-snapshot file
would invalidate the entire prompt cache prefix, forcing a full re-read of
system prompt + tools + rules on the next turn. For long sessions this can
waste thousands of cached tokens per turn.

## LLM API Calls in Pipeline Code

When the project's Python scripts call LLM APIs (Claude, OpenAI, etc.):

- Route by complexity: Haiku for classification/extraction, Sonnet for analysis, Opus only for multi-step reasoning
- Set explicit budget limits before batch processing
- Use prompt caching (`cache_control: {"type": "ephemeral"}`) for system prompts >1024 tokens
- Retry only on transient errors (rate limit, connection, server errors) — fail fast on auth/validation errors
- Log model selection decisions for cost threshold tuning
